description: JWT authentication and protected route conventions
globs: app/api/**/*.py
alwaysApply: false
---

# Authentication

- Mount new business endpoints on `protected_router` in `app/api/v1/router.py` — not on `api_router` unless intentionally public.
- Public routes: health checks, `POST /api/v1/auth/register`, and `POST /api/v1/auth/login`.
- **Caller vs target user:** JWT / `current_user` = authenticated caller; `user_id` in body or form = target user whose data is scoped (query search, import ownership). Do not conflate them.
- Do not use request `user_id` as proof of identity — identity comes only from JWT.
- Use `current_user: User = Depends(get_current_user)` in handlers only when caller identity is needed (audit, future per-caller authorization).
- Raise `AuthenticationError` / `AuthorizationError` from services; let `AppError` handlers map to 401/403 — do not catch in endpoints except 404 translations.
- Add tests with the `auth_headers` fixture for any new protected endpoint.

```python
# Good — protected route on protected_router; target user in body
@router.post("")
async def query_context(
    body: QueryRequest,
    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),
) -> QueryResponse:
    user = await db.get(User, body.user_id)  # target user for search scope
    ...

# Bad — mounting business logic on api_router without JWT
api_router.include_router(my_feature.router, prefix="/my-feature")

# Bad — treating body user_id as the authenticated caller
async def query_context(body: QueryRequest, db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db)):
    result = await query_service.answer_query(db, body.query, body.user_id)
    # missing JWT gate; body.user_id is not authentication
```
